Bias Is Not a Bug
Selection, Production Lines, and the False Marketing of Neutral AI
June 2026

Abstract
The claim that an artificial intelligence system is “unbiased” or “completely objective” is not a technical description. It is a marketing position. Every engineered system — from a car to a burger to a large language model — is the product of selection, and selection is directional. The question has never been whether an AI system is biased. The question is: who selected the bias, by what process, under what incentives, with what disclosures, and with what right of challenge? This paper argues that neutrality is not the absence of bias but a claim about how bias has been selected, measured, disclosed, constrained, and made accountable. The failure to understand this distinction has produced a public discourse in which one system’s bias is presented as objectivity, another system’s bias is presented as censorship, and consumers are left without the tools to evaluate either claim.

1. The Problem
On 6 June 2026, a user on X posted the following observation about an AI system called Grok:

“something i love about @grok is the fact that no other LLM will ever give me a completely unbiased answer — for example, its incredibly refreshing to ask grok about a political matter that i saw in the news and form a conclusive, fact-based opinion based on objective evidence”

This post received thousands of views. It is not an unusual view. Variants of it appear daily across social media, comment sections, and technology forums. It reflects a genuine experience: the user asked an AI system a question about a political topic and received an answer that felt honest and direct. But the post also contains a category error so fundamental that it warrants a full examination.
The user is not describing neutrality. They are describing satisfaction. The answer they received confirmed or articulated a view they found credible. That felt like objectivity. But confirmation is not neutrality. It is, in fact, one of the most reliable signatures of a system calibrated to a particular audience’s expectations. An AI trained to give answers that feel unbiased to a specific demographic will feel unbiased to that demographic regardless of how biased those answers actually are. The sensation of objectivity and the fact of objectivity are not the same thing.
This paper is not primarily an argument about Grok, or about any specific AI product. It is an argument about how bias works, why everything engineered contains it, and why the concept of a “completely unbiased” AI system is not merely improbable but definitionally incoherent under any serious analysis.

2. Bias Is Not Optional: The Logic of Selection
Bias is not a malfunction. It is not the result of political interference, corporate cowardice, or ideological capture, though those forces can shape its specific character. Bias is the necessary consequence of selection. Any system that must produce an output from a range of possible outputs has made choices about which outputs are acceptable, probable, or preferred. Those choices are directional. Direction is bias.
Consider a Ford car. A Ford car is biased:
–	toward roads with tarmac surfaces
–	toward petrol or diesel as fuel (in most legacy models)
–	toward average adult body dimensions in its ergonomic design
–	toward the safety legislation of its primary markets
–	toward manufacturing cost targets set by the company
–	toward repair networks that exist in countries where it is sold
–	toward the brand positioning Ford wishes to occupy

None of this is a scandal. It would be strange if it were otherwise. A car that tries to work on all surfaces, with all fuels, for all body types, at all price points, in all regulatory environments would not be a car. It would be a design document full of contradictions. The act of making a car — the act of bringing it from possibility to production — is the act of selecting. And every selection excludes.
Consider a Burger King burger. A Burger King burger is biased:
–	toward shelf life and supply-chain stability over fresh ingredients
–	toward the salt, fat, and sugar profile that drives repeat consumption
–	toward mass production at scale, which constrains ingredient variety
–	toward price points accessible in its target markets
–	toward cooking speeds compatible with fast-food service

Again, no scandal. The burger is what it is because choices were made. Different choices would produce a different burger. The choices reflect commercial incentives, supply constraints, regulatory requirements, and accumulated market research. The burger is not objective. It is not trying to be. Nobody argues that Burger King has a duty to produce a “neutral burger.”
Now consider a large language model. A large language model is biased:
–	toward the corpus on which it was trained (which overrepresents certain languages, time periods, demographics, and publication formats)
–	toward the filtering decisions applied to that corpus (which excluded certain content)
–	toward the preferences of the human labellers who rated outputs during training
–	toward the reinforcement learning objectives used to shape its behaviour
–	toward the refusal policies set by the deploying company
–	toward the commercial risk tolerance of that company
–	toward the system prompts applied in specific deployment contexts
–	toward the expectations of the user base the system was optimised to serve

Every one of these is a selection. Every selection is directional. Every direction is a bias. The question is not whether the model is biased. The model is biased. The question is what the bias is, who chose it, and whether those choices are disclosed and contestable.

3. The Taxonomy of Bias
Public discourse about AI bias has become almost entirely fixated on political bias: does the model give left-leaning answers or right-leaning answers? This is a real concern and deserves examination. But it is one category among many, and focussing on it exclusively creates a dangerously incomplete picture.
3.1 Dataset Bias
Training data is not neutral. The internet overrepresents English, overrepresents the Global North, overrepresents certain decades, overrepresents published and indexed material over oral traditions and informal knowledge, and underrepresents populations with lower rates of digital content production. A model trained on this corpus will reflect its shape.
3.2 Labeller Bias
In reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), human raters evaluate model outputs and their preferences shape the model’s behaviour. Those raters are not a representative sample of humanity. They are a sample of people who agreed to work on labelling tasks, at the rates offered, in the locations where that work was available. Their cultural context, their educational background, their prior experiences, and their interpretation of instruction all influence what they rate as good, clear, safe, or helpful.
3.3 Optimisation Bias
A model trained to maximise a particular objective will become very good at that objective and potentially worse at everything the objective does not capture. If the objective is “user satisfaction,” the model may learn to tell people what they want to hear. If the objective is “safety,” the model may become overly cautious in ways that reduce utility. The objective is a bias.
3.4 Commercial Bias
AI systems are products. Products have commercial incentives. A system deployed by a company will be shaped by that company’s risk tolerance, liability concerns, brand positioning, target market, and revenue model. These incentives are not neutral. They produce directional effects on what the system will and will not say.
3.5 Validation Bias
Perhaps the most important category for understanding the tweet that opened this paper: validation bias is the tendency of a system to produce outputs that feel neutral or objective to its intended audience. A system calibrated to the expectations and assumptions of a particular group will feel refreshingly honest to that group and potentially biased to those outside it. This is not neutrality. It is optimisation for one group’s perception of neutrality. Validation bias is particularly dangerous because it is invisible to the people it is designed to satisfy. It feels like truth.
3.6 Interface Bias
The way a system presents its outputs — confident prose versus hedged probabilistic language, citations versus assertions, long explanations versus short verdicts — shapes how authoritative those outputs appear. A system that presents all answers in the same confident register regardless of the underlying uncertainty is biasing the user toward overconfidence. A system that appends lengthy caveats to every output is biasing the user toward dismissal. Format is not neutral.

4. The Production Line
When a user asks an AI model a question about a political topic and receives an answer, they see one thing: a paragraph of text. What they do not see is the production line that generated it.
That production line includes, at minimum:
–	the training corpus and its inherent distributions
–	the filtering and moderation applied to that corpus
–	the labelling process and the demographics and instructions of the labellers
–	the reinforcement learning objective and its operationalisation
–	the refusal policy and the risk calculus behind it
–	the system prompt applied to this deployment
–	the ranking and sampling parameters that determine which token comes next
–	the commercial and reputational incentives of the company that deployed it

The answer the user receives is the end of that conveyor belt. It is not a thought. It is not objective observation. It is a product. Like all products, it is the materialisation of choices made long before the user’s question arrived.
This does not make AI systems useless. Cars are also the materialisation of prior choices and we find them useful. The point is that the prior choices matter, and they should be visible, disclosable, and contestable. The user asking a question deserves to know something about the production line they are querying, not because it will always change their behaviour, but because informed use is categorically different from credulous use.

5. The Marketing Move
Given the above, the claim that any specific AI system gives “completely unbiased” answers deserves scrutiny as a product claim, not just as a philosophical position.
There is a specific rhetorical structure at work in the AI bias discourse:
–	Other systems: “biased,” “censored,” “woke,” unwilling to give honest answers
–	Our system: “unbiased,” “truthful,” “objective,” refreshingly honest

This is not a neutral technical description. It is a positioning statement. It is the same move made in every market: our product gives you what you actually want, theirs makes you eat something inferior for reasons that have nothing to do with your benefit.
The problem is not that AI companies market their products. All companies market their products. The problem is that the specific claim of objectivity is systematically misleading, because:
–	Objectivity is not a product feature. It is not something that can be implemented, tested, certified, or shipped.
–	The claim “completely unbiased” is not falsifiable as stated. There is no agreed standard against which it can be measured.
–	The audience most likely to believe the claim is the audience the system was designed to satisfy — which means the claim feels most credible to exactly the people it is most effectively misleading.

A system that tells its target audience that it is unbiased, and whose target audience believes it, has not achieved objectivity. It has achieved effective marketing.

6. What Neutrality Actually Means
Neutrality is not the absence of bias. Under any serious definition, neutrality is a claim about how bias has been selected, measured, disclosed, constrained, and made accountable.
A useful analogy is the legal system. A judge is not neutral in the sense of having no prior knowledge, no interpretive framework, no cultural context, and no analytical preferences. That would not be a judge; it would be a random number generator. A judge is neutral — or aspires to neutrality — in a procedural sense: disclosed conflicts of interest, defined rules of evidence, stated reasoning, right of appeal, precedent, and accountability to higher review. The neutrality is not in the absence of a perspective. It is in the accountability structure around that perspective.
Applied to AI systems, this suggests that a more honest and more useful set of questions than “is this AI unbiased?” would be:
–	What are the known biases in the training data, and are they disclosed?
–	What were the criteria for the RLHF labelling process, and who performed it?
–	What is the refusal policy, and how was it developed?
–	What commercial incentives shape the system’s outputs?
–	How is the system tested for bias on defined benchmarks?
–	What right of challenge does a user have when they believe an answer is wrong?

A system that answers these questions transparently is closer to neutral in any meaningful sense than a system that simply claims to be neutral.

7. The Regulatory Dimension
The claim that AI systems are unbiased or objective does not exist in a legal vacuum. Depending on jurisdiction and use case, it may engage consumer protection law, advertising standards, equality legislation, and emerging AI-specific regulation.
7.1 UK Position
The UK does not currently have a single cross-cutting AI-specific statute. The government’s AI white paper, published in 2023, set out a principles-based approach relying on existing sectoral regulators rather than a new AI-specific regulator. However, existing legal frameworks continue to apply.
The Equality Act 2010 applies where AI-generated outputs produce discriminatory outcomes on protected characteristics. The UK GDPR and Data Protection Act 2018 require that automated processing of personal data be fair and transparent. The Consumer Rights Act 2015 and consumer protection regulations apply where AI products are sold with misleading claims. The Advertising Standards Authority (ASA) applies the UK Code of Non-broadcast Advertising (CAP Code) to online advertising, including claims about AI products; misleading claims about the capabilities or objectivity of AI systems would potentially fall within its remit.
7.2 EU Position
The EU AI Act, which entered into force on 1 August 2024, establishes a risk-based framework for AI systems operating in the European market. High-risk AI systems — including those used in employment, education, law enforcement, and critical infrastructure — are subject to requirements including transparency, human oversight, and bias testing. The Act also prohibits certain AI practices outright and introduces obligations for general-purpose AI models. The framing is explicitly oriented toward fundamental rights, safety, and human-centric design.
7.3 The Gap Between Law and Practice
The regulatory frameworks exist. Their application to the specific claim that an AI system is “completely unbiased” is underdeveloped. Advertising standards regulators have not yet systematically engaged with AI objectivity claims as a category of potentially misleading advertising. Data protection authorities have not yet produced detailed guidance on what “fair” automated processing means in the context of large language models. The tools exist. The enforcement focus has not yet arrived.
This is likely to change. As AI systems become more embedded in consequential decisions — employment screening, credit assessment, medical triage, legal advice — the question of who made which choices in the production line will become a legal question as well as a philosophical one. The companies that have built their brands on claims of objectivity will face difficult questions when those claims are tested against defined standards.

8. What This Means in Practice
None of this means that AI systems are all equally biased, that no progress can be made on bias reduction, or that users should refuse to engage with AI tools. It means something more modest and more actionable:
–	When an AI system feels honest and unbiased to you, that feeling is data about your relationship to the system’s calibration, not data about the system’s objectivity.
–	When an AI system is described as “unbiased” in marketing materials, treat that as a product claim requiring evidence, not a technical specification.
–	When comparing AI systems on the axis of bias, ask what benchmarks were used, what the systems were compared against, and who conducted the comparison.
–	When using AI for consequential decisions — medical, legal, financial, political — treat its outputs as one input among several, not as an objective verdict.
–	When a company claims that its AI gives you “complete objectivity” while others give you “censored” answers, ask what the company’s incentive is in making that claim, and who is being told they are finally getting the truth.

The last point matters most. “Finally, an AI that tells the truth” is a remarkably effective marketing message, especially in an environment of genuine distrust of institutions. It is effective precisely because it is unfalsifiable: if the AI confirms your beliefs, that is evidence of its honesty; if it challenges your beliefs, that is evidence of its bias. The claim is constructed to be immune to counter-evidence. That is not how objectivity works. That is how ideology works.

Conclusion
Bias is not a bug introduced into otherwise neutral systems by bad actors. It is a structural property of every system that must select among possible outputs. Cars are biased. Burgers are biased. Exams are biased. Search engines are biased. Legal systems are biased. Large language models are biased. The question has never been whether bias exists. The question is who chose it, under what pressures, with what disclosure, and with what accountability.
The marketing category of “unbiased AI” is not a technical achievement. It is a rhetorical position, usually aimed at users who feel that other systems are suppressing something they deserve to hear. The system that makes that claim is not neutral. It is calibrated — specifically, it is calibrated to feel neutral to a particular audience. Calibration to the expectations of a target audience is not neutrality. It is product design.
Neutrality, properly understood, is not silence on difficult questions. It is an accountability structure: disclosed conflicts of interest, stated methodology, defined benchmarks, right of challenge, and responsibility for outcomes. By that standard, no currently available AI system is neutral. Some are more transparent than others. Some are more rigorously tested than others. Some are more honest about their own limitations than others. These are meaningful distinctions, and they matter.
The question is not whether an AI system is biased. The question is who selected the bias, by what process, under what incentives, with what disclosures, and with what right of challenge.
Until that question can be answered clearly and publicly for every major AI system, the claim of complete objectivity should be understood for what it is: not a technical description, but a sales pitch.
